1. Summary

Objective

This project will investigate the relationship between proximity to petrochemical plants, racial and ethnic minority status, and cancer rates within an area. We will examine Leukemia cancer, which is known to be caused by petrochemical plants.

We will examine cancer rates in relation to social vulnerability index in the eleven parishes of Cancer Alley in Louisiana in comparison with the rest of Louisiana and Vermont, a state that does not have petrochemical plants.

Research Question: What is the relationship between proximity to petrochemical plants, racial and ethnic minority status, and cancer rates within Cancer Alley as compared to the rest of Louisiana and a state with no petrochemical plants?

Motivation: Petrochemical plants are disproportionately located in predominantly Black communities, leading to increased air pollution and higher cancer incidence rates, acting as a form of environmental racism. Understanding these relationships will help us enact equitable change in the future.

Datasets

Dataset 1

The first dataset we will be examining is the State Cancer Profiles dataset from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the National Institutes of Health (NIH) National Cancer Institute (https://statecancerprofiles.cancer.gov/index.html). This dataset was developed to display geographic patterns of cancer incident, risk, and mortality. Specifically, we will be analyzing the datasets for Louisiana and Vermont. This dataset was developed to display geographic patterns of cancer incident, risk, and mortality. The dataset was created from public health surveillance systems using published reports and files for public use.

We intend to work with this dataset in order to examine cancer rates by county for multiple states. With this dataset, we intend to answer the question: How does proximity to petrochemical plants influence cancer rates in a county? For each parish, we will examine the number of cases per 100,000 people as well as the average number of cases annually. This data will allow us to answer our research question by comparing the cases per 100,000 people to the number of petrochemical plants per county.

Dataset 2

We will also examine datasets from the EPA TRI Toxic Tracker. (https://edap.epa.gov/public/extensions/TRIToxicsTracker/TRIToxicsTracker.html#continue) From this portal, we have identified facilities in Louisiana that deal mainly with the petrochemicals, methanol, ethylene, propylene, and butadiene. This dataset is a compilation put together by the EPA of Toxic Release Iventory (TRI) numbers that are submitted by industrial facilities to the EPA.

We intend to work with this dataset in order to examine the distribution of petrochemical facilities across the US and where petrochemical facilities are most concentrated. With this dataset, we intend to answer the question: How does the density of petrochemical plants in a parish influence the parish's cancer rates? We will examine the number of petrochemical facilities in each parish and compare it to the cancer rates found in dataset 1 to answer our research questions.

Dataset 3

We will also examine the CDC's Social Vulnerability Index. (https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/place-health/php/svi/svi-data-documentation-download.html) This dataset was created by the Center for Disease Control's Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry, and it describes communities' social vulnerability to disasters and disease outbreaks. It ranks census tracts by their social vulnerability based on social factors and calculates an overall social vulnerability index, as well as social vulnerability indices based on four themes: Socioeconomic Status, Racial and Ethnic Minority Status, Household Characteristics, and Housing Type and Transportation.

We will examine the Social Vulnerability Index (SVI) based on Racial and Ethnic Minority Status by parish/county. With this dataset, we intend to answer the question: How does the density of petrochemical plants in a geographic area correlate with the SVI of the surrounding populations with respect to the Racial and Ethnic Miority Status theme in influencing cancer rates in a given region? Historically, industrial facilities, such as petrochemical plants, have often been sited near communities with predominantly African American and Hispanic populations. This pattern of environmental racism is a critical factor believed to contribute to the elevated cancer rates in Cancer Alley.

Hypothesis

We hypothesize that parishes with the most petrochemical plants and higher social vulnerability indexes will have the highest rates of cancer.

In this ETL section, we read in all of our datasets, specified in the comments of the specific code block, and cleaned the data. Cleaning the data consisted of removing rows or columns that contained NaN values, dropping columns that were not going to be used, and renaming columns for clarity. We end ETL of each dataset with a discussion of the dataset and how we cleaned it, what we will use it for, and issues we faced when cleaning the dataset.

Data Discussion: In this dataset, we compare rates of all cancer types for both Louisiana and Vermont. This is important to determine the difference in cancer rates in terms of petrochemical plants. Vermont has no industrial plants, whereas Louisiana has a significant amount of industrial plants. We see this comparison in a side-by-side histogram later in the notebook. As a way to keep our data as concise as possible, we are looking at three columns of data in each set. We are looking at parish/county, which is important because some parishes contain more petrochemical plants than others, such as the 11 parishes that encompass what is known as "Cancer Alley," the part of the state with the most petrochemical plants. Our second variable is Cases Per 100,000. This allows us to look at how many incidents of all cancer types per 100,000 people. The last variable is Average Annual Count. This variable is important because the dataset spans 5 years, so it is helpful to look at the average for every year throughout all parishes. We also have two rows for the cancer cases in the entirety of Louisiana as well as the United States. These are helpful baselines that can be used to compare where each parish falls compared to the local and national average of incidences among all cancer types. These datasets will allow us to observe numbers in cancer alley parishes vs non-cancer alley parishes to see if there is a significant uptick in cancer incidences where there are more petrochemical plants. We also compare this to Vermont's cancer statistics where there are little to no petrochemical plants to see if there is a correlation between cancer incidences and number of petrochemical plants. Issues we faced during using this dataset include order of code to replace NaNs and then also drop the rows. Deciding whether to drop rows or columns was a large issue we faced because we did not want to lose a significant amount of data by dropping a whole column, but dropping rows may also cause us to lose significant data points.

Data Discussion: This dataset compares Louisiana cancer rates of Leukemia and Vermont cancer rates of Leukemia. Leukemia, specifically, has been linked to proximity to petrochemical plants. This will give us a more intentional look into the cancer rates of both states. Because cancer can be caused by a multidude of things and not just environmental factors, looking at all cancer types is not enough. Leukemia can help us to narrow down any significant differences between the two states. The challenges we faced while tidying the data were primarily deciding whether to drop rows or columns for our NaN values, deciding what rows and columns to drop because they were not relevant to our research anaylsis, and variable types from conversion to a CSV file. For our rows and columns in our all cancer types datasets, there were NaN values for a rural/urban category for our baseline state and national rows but not for the parishes. Because we wanted to keep the qualitative data for the baseline rows, we decided to drop the columns that had NaN values. Then, we decided which columns would not be helpful to us and dropped the rest of the unnecessary columns. But, for our Leukemia dataset, there were more NaN values because there were more concentrated data points, and thus, the data was suppressed for privacy reasons. We handled this issue by dropping the unnecessary columns first because we had already decided which columns we would observe. Then, we decided to drop rows that contained NaN values, so parishes where Leukemia data is suppressed will not be taken into account for that certain cancer type. However, this should not be a major issue because the dataset for all cancer types had no NaNs, so we still have data to go on, but we just don't have specific data for Leukemia for those specific parishes. We also had a few issues with dtypes of our three columns for the Leukemia datasets. Originally, the dtypes were returning as all objects for the Leukemia dataset but not the all cancer types dataset. This is because it was converted to a CSV from a google sheet, so the numbers were read as strings instead of numbers. This was corrected by converting the variables to numeric variables, which also subsequently fixed our summary statistics as well as the dtypes returned.

Data Discussion: This dataset allows us to see petrochemical plant density in the state of Louisiana. This dataset originally included every industrial facility in Louisiana that is required to submit a toxic release report to the EPA every year. However, we are exclusively looking at petrochemical plants. Thus, we looked at the chemicals each facility reported to have dealt with and picked the top 4 chemicals that are handled by petrochemical plants. Problems with this dataset include the fact that the dataset might not be the most comprehensive data. Louisiana does not have a public record of all petrochemical plants with their respective parish locations as well as what chemical they handle. Thus, this data had to be sifted through to find four of the basic petrochemicals to only include those in the dataset. The plants that reported actually handling these four petrochemicals totals 258 industrial plants with over half of those industrial plants concentrated to 11 parishes.

Modeling

Model Question: Is there a statistically significant relationship between SVI, number of petrochemical plants, and cancer incidence rates within a given parish?

First we are creating a dataframe called "Louisiana Parish Data." This dataframe will contain parish names, cancer rates, SVI data, and petrochemical plant data for each county we will use this dataframe to create a linear regression model.

Since each dataset names parishes differently, we merged the datasets based on their FIPS codes, or the numerical name for each parish.

combined_all_data = pd.concat([merged_VT,merged_LA])
combined_all_data.rename(columns = {"Average Annual Count":"Average_Annual_Count", "2024 Population": "Population", "SVI by Racial and Ethnic Minority Status": "SVI", "Petrochemical plants": "Petrochemical_Plants"} ,inplace=True)
# Convert all required columns to numeric
combined_all_data['Average_Annual_Count'] = pd.to_numeric(
    combined_all_data['Average_Annual_Count'],
    errors='coerce'
)
combined_all_data['Petrochemical_Plants'] = pd.to_numeric(
    combined_all_data['Petrochemical_Plants'],
    errors='coerce'
)
combined_all_data['SVI'] = pd.to_numeric(
    combined_all_data['SVI'],
    errors='coerce'
)
combined_all_data['Population'] = pd.to_numeric(
    combined_all_data['Population'],
    errors='coerce'
)
combined_all_data
In[]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

# Define the formula: log(Expected_Cases) = Intercept + beta1*Plant_Density + beta2*SVI + log(Population)
# 'offset=np.log(df["Population"])' transforms the model to estimate a rate
model_formula = 'Average_Annual_Count ~ Petrochemical_Plants + SVI'

# Create and fit the Negative Binomial model
negbin_model = smf.glm(
    formula=model_formula,
    data=combined_all_data,
    family=sm.families.NegativeBinomial(link=sm.genmod.families.links.log()),
    exposure=combined_all_data['Population']
).fit()

# Print the summary to check for statistical significance
print("Negative Binomial Regression Results\n")
print(negbin_model.summary())

Model Discussion

According to the results of our model above, there is not a statistically significant relationship between Petrochemical Plants and Cancer rates or between SVI and cancer rates for a given area. However, there are limitations to this study that we believe could be influencing these results as other researchers have found different results for similar research questions (see Further Reading section). While our study did not find a statistically significant relationship between presence of petrochemical plants in a county/parish and its rate of cancer incidences, we know from other studies that air pollution is linked to cancer rates. There could be other factors we did not account for in this study influencing our results. For example, air pollution and physical proximity of neighborhoods to petrochemical plants are likely linked to higher incidence rates of cancer, but we did not account for these variables. Presence of petrochemical plants alone in a county may not be enough to explain the diproportionately high rates of cancer in Louisiana. Future research should examine a more robust range of variables to determine which specific hazards are responsible for the increased incidence rates of cancer in Louisiana.

Why we chose Negative Binomial Regression: A Negative Binomial regression model is a generalized linear model used to count data where there is overdispersion, meaning the variance is greater than the mean. This was the most appropriate model because cancer incidence rates are likely to be influenced by a number of unobserved factors. This model estimates relationships between predictors and the log of expected count, helping understand factors influencing rare or high-variance events. This model also included population to estimate rate of incidence as opposed to raw counts. However, we found the p-values of both petrochemical plants and SVI to be much larger than the 0.05 threshold, indicating that in this study, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Conclusions

Louisiana has higher rates of cancer than the national average, especially when we look at leukemia rates, a cancer type known to be associated with exposure to petrochemicals. Louisiana also has one of the largest concentrations of petrochemical plants in the country. This study found, however, that presence alone of petrochemical plants in a county is not enough to explain the county's rates of cancer incidences. Future studies should include other variables such as air pollution.
